'''Johan Fredrik Gørrissen''' (18 March 1907 – 2 April 1982) was a Norwegian chemical engineer and industrial leader.
He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]], a son of ship-owner Willy Gørrissen and Magdalene Lothe. He graduated in chemical engineering from the [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]] in 1935. He worked as an engineer for [[Christiania Spigerverk]] in the 1930s, and later assumed various leading positions for [[Elkem|Elektrokemisk]].
During the [[German occupation of Norway]] he took part in the leadership of [[Milorg]], until he was arrested in October 1942,<ref name=kd-288>{{cite book |title=Krigens Dagbok |chapter=Det store slag mot Milorg |language=Norwegian |editor=[[Per Voksø|Voksø, Per]] |year=1984 |publisher=Det Beste |location=Oslo |isbn=82-7010-166-4 |page=288 }}</ref> and sent to the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] in Germany in 1943.<ref>{{cite book|editor=[[Kristian Ottosen|Ottosen, Kristian]]|title=Nordmenn i fangenskap 1940–1945|edition=2nd|year=2004|publisher=Universitetsforlaget|location=Oslo|language=Norwegian|isbn=82-15-00288-9|page=259}}</ref> He was decorated with the [[King's Medal for Courage in the Cause of Freedom]] for his contributions during [[World War II]].<ref name=hvem>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1973|title=Gørrissen, Johan Fredrik |encyclopedia=[[Hvem er hvem?]]|editor=Steenstrup, Bjørn|publisher=Aschehoug|location=Oslo|url=http://runeberg.org/hvemerhvem/1973/0197.html|page=197 |language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref>
He died in April 1982 and was buried at [[Ris, Oslo|Ris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/index.php?language=engelsk|title=Cemeteries in Norway|publisher=DIS-Norge|accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref>
