{{Infobox company | name = Ruff 'n' Tumble | logo = File:RNT-Logo2.png | type =[[Private company]] | predecessor = | successor = | founder = [[Adenike Ogunlesi]] | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | fate = | area_served = Nigeria | key_people = Adenike Ogunlesi | industry = [[Apparel]] | products = Children's Clothing | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = 150+ | parent =Gatimo Limited | divisions = | subsid = | footnotes = | intl = | homepage ={{url||http://www.ruffntumblekids.com/}} | caption = | foundation = 1996<!-- {{Start date|YY|MM}} --> | location_city = [[Ikeja]], [[Lagos State]] | location_country = Nigeria | locations =15 Stores | location = }}
'''Ruff 'n' Tumble''' is a Nigerian clothing brand that specialises in children's apparel<ref name =Businessday>{{cite news|url=http://businessdayonline.com/2014/07/adenike-ogunlesi-leading-contemporary-kids-clothing-brand-in-nigeria/#.VJvGLCYIE|publisher=Businessday|title= Adenike Ogunlesi, leading contemporary kids clothing brand in Nigeria|author=Kemi Ajumobi|accessdate=December 24, 2014}}</ref> <ref name=ventures>{{cite web|url=http://www.ventures-africa.com/2012/09/building-an-african-clothing-empire-adenike-ogunlesis-ruff-ntumble/|title=building an african clothing empire Adenike Ogunlesi|website=Ventures Africa|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{ cite news|url=http://www.punchng.com/business/ruff-n-tumble-introduces-promo-for-kids/|title=Ruff 'n' Tumble introduces promo for kids|accessdate=December 24, 2014|publisher=Punch}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ng/books?id=z2AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT4&lpg=PT4&dq=Ruff+%27n%27+Tumble+Ghana&source=bl&ots=n0WFzm_Vcd&sig=uE78aV6vcLdpqoBBcA3cNwRfxN8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lmGcVJD0C4r_UKf-gMAL&ved=0CBwQ6AEwATgK|title=Democracy at Large: Listen to Africa|author=Don Tudoran|year=2005}}</ref>
==History== Ruff 'n' Tumble was founded in 1996 when Adenike Ogunlesi needed pyjamas for her kids.<ref name=ventures/><ref name=punch>{{cite news|url=http://www.punchng.com/spice/essence/government-does-not-support-the-garment-industry-adenike-ogunlesi/|title=Government does not support the garment industry-Adenike Ogunlesi|publisher=The Punch|accessdate=December 25, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141130004020/http://www.punchng.com/spice/essence/government-does-not-support-the-garment-industry-adenike-ogunlesi/|archivedate=November 30, 2014|df=}}</ref><ref name=independent>{{cite news|title=How we started Ruff 'n' Tumble by Mrs Ogunlesi|url=http://dailyindependentnig.com/2013/12/started-ruff-n-tumble-mrs-ogunlesi/|publisher=Daily Independent|date=February 1, 2013|accessdate=November 28, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129140832/http://dailyindependentnig.com/2013/12/started-ruff-n-tumble-mrs-ogunlesi/|archivedate=November 29, 2014|df=}}</ref> Already making clothes for women,<ref name=freedom/> she decided to make the clothes with assistance from her mother, a [[dressmaker]].<ref name=ventures/> She initially used local materials including Ankara and [[Adire (textile art)|Adire]].<ref name=independent/> Production started and services were later expanded to other Nigerian families with kids. The clothing production (for children from the ages of 0 to 16), gradually progressed from her house (selling from the boot of her car) <ref name=ventures/> to a location in [[Victoria Island (Nigeria)|Victoria Island, Lagos]].<ref name=freedom>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialfreedominspiration.com/resources/success-stories/adenike-ogunlesi-ruff-n-tumble/|website=Financial Freedom Inspiration|title=Adenike Ogunlesi – Ruff N Tumble|accessdate=December 24, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141122075836/http://www.financialfreedominspiration.com/resources/success-stories/adenike-ogunlesi-ruff-n-tumble/|archivedate=November 22, 2014|df=}}</ref> Ruff 'n' Tumble operates a ware house, factory, distribution<ref name=summit/> and has more than 50 employees.<ref name=ventures/> It has also extended branches to [[Surulere]] in Lagos,<ref name=forwardtimes/> and [[Ikeja]],<ref name=Businessday/> as well as, other Nigerian cities, including, [[Ibadan]], [[Kano]] and [[Port Harcourt]].<ref name= bellanaija/> The Company has about 15 branch locations across the country.<ref name=summit>{{cite web|url=http://summit.nnew.org/?p=summit-speakers|website=Summit Speakers|title=Adenike Ogunlesi|accessdate= November 28, 2014}}</ref> Ruff 'n' Tumble also owns the brands "Trendsetters" and "NaijaBoysz"<ref name=ventures/><ref name = forwardtimes>{{cite news|url=http://forwardtimesonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=248:adenike-ogunlesi-ruff-n-tumble&catid=105:business-news&Itemid=162|title=Adenike Ogunlesi: Ruff 'n' Tumble|publisher=Houston Forward Times|accessdate=December 24, 2014}}</ref>(a clothing range for young boys aged 8–16).<ref name=bellanaija>{{cite news| url=http://www.bellanaija.com/2010/11/26/ruff-‘n’-tumble-introduces-new-brand-naijaboysz-and-opens-new-stores-in-port-harcourt-lagos/|publisher=BellaNaija|title=Advertisement Ruff ‘n’ Tumble introduces new brand "NaijaBoysZ" and opens new stores in Port Harcourt & Lagos|accessdate=December 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opencityafrica.com/speakers/11-speakers/16-adenike-ogunlesi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226024207/http://www.opencityafrica.com/speakers/11-speakers/16-adenike-ogunlesi|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2014-12-26|title=Adenike Ogunlesi|website=Open Africa}}</ref> Ruff 'n' Tumble partnered with Nigerian Employers Consultative Association (NECA) and Industrial Training Fund (ITF) to help reduce unemployment in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/news/national-news/188979-40-million-nigerian-youths-still-unemployed-says-neca|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141225191037/http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/news/national-news/188979-40-million-nigerian-youths-still-unemployed-says-neca|dead-url=yes|archive-date=December 25, 2014|title=40 million Nigerians still unemployed|publisher=Nigerian Guardian|date=December 3, 2014|author=News Agency of Nigeria|accessdate=December 25, 2014}}</ref>
